Loading data …

pro <- read.delim("proteinGroups.txt")
pro <- pro[pro$Reverse !="+",]
pep <- read.delim("peptides.txt")
pep <- pep[pep$Reverse !="+",]


# melt peptide table
pep.melt <- melt(pep, id.vars=c("Sequence","Proteins","Leading.razor.protein"), 
                 measure.vars=grep("^Intensity.",names(pep), value=TRUE))
pep.melt$variable <- gsub('^Intensity.', '', pep.melt$variable, perl=T)
pep.melt$condition <- gsub('_.$', '', pep.melt$variable, perl=T)

pep.melt$value[pep.melt$value == 0] <- NA # 0 means peptide was not detected

pep.melt.narm <- subset(pep.melt, !is.na(value))


sampleInfo <- unique(pep.melt[,c("variable", "condition")])
sampleInfo$Run <- 1:nrow(sampleInfo)
sampleInfo$condition <- gsub("_.$", "", sampleInfo$variable)

In this practise the objetive is to do an statistical analysis of the data using different normalization method, comparing the results between them and also between the analysis of raw data. The normalized data and also the raw data come from the tutorial, this is why we will only focus in the statistical analysis and not in the normalization of the data.

In adition, in the tutorial the analysis was done using pvalue, but here we are going to use adj.pvalue in some cases we will see. In the new normalize method we will use the adj.value. The reason of use adj.pvalue instead pvalue is the number of samples we have, with 2039 test the adjust of pvalue is necessary to generate more realistic results.

So the 5 different method used to do the analysis are:

-Loess The same example did in the class, with loess-G-normalized data.

-Loess + adj.pvalue The same but using adj.pvalue.

-Raw data Using log2-normalized txt file, like the example available in the tutorial box.

-RAW data + adj.value* The same but using adj.pvalue to compare.

-VSN Using VSN-G-Normalized txt file.

-RLR Using RLR-G-Normalized txt file.

VSN and RLR method was random selected, both of them were analyzed using adj.pvalue as we said before.

Statistical test (MSstats) for differential protein abundance. Loess, tutorial example.

#detach("package:Normalyzer", unload=TRUE)

# Loess normalization
pept_loG <- read.delim("normalization_peptides/Loess-G-normalized.txt")

# remove peptides non-unique for groups or proteins, select Sequence, Proteins and Intensities columns, and melt table
mloG <- melt(subset(pept_loG, Unique..Groups. == "yes" & Unique..Proteins. == "yes", select=c(1,2,6:ncol(pept_loG))), id.vars=1:2)
mloG$value <- 2^mloG$value

#pep2prot <- aggregate(mloG[,4], by=list(mloG$Protein, mloG$variable), function(x) sum(x, na.rm=TRUE))
#prots <- cast(pep2prot, Group.1 ~ Group.2, sum)
#colnames(pep.prot.melt) <- c("Leading.razor.protein", "SampleName", "Condition", "sumIntensity")

# add columns for MSstats
mloG$PrecursorCharge <- 2
mloG$FragmentIon <- NA
mloG$ProductCharge <- NA
mloG$IsotopeLabelType <- "L"
mloG <- merge(mloG, sampleInfo, by="variable",all=TRUE)

# Compare 
mloG_10col <- mloG[,c(3,2,5:9,1,10,4)]
colnames(mloG_10col) <- c("ProteinName", "PeptideSequence", "PrecursorCharge","FragmentIon", "ProductCharge","IsotopeLabelType", "Condition","BioReplicate", "Run", "Intensity")


quant_mloG <- dataProcess(mloG_10col, normalization=FALSE)
##                        
##   Summary of Features :
##                          count
## # of Protein              2046
## # of Peptides/Protein     1-85
## # of Transitions/Peptide   1-1
##                       
##   Summary of Samples :
##                            EcoUPS1 EcoUPS2
## # of MS runs                     4       4
## # of Biological Replicates       4       4
## # of Technical Replicates        1       1
levels(quant_mloG$ProcessedData$GROUP_ORIGINAL)
## [1] "EcoUPS1" "EcoUPS2"
comparison<-matrix(c(-1,1),nrow=1)
row.names(comparison) <- "UPS2 vs UPS1"



#scopeOfTechReplication="expanded", scopeOfBioReplication="restricted", 
comp_mloG <- groupComparison(contrast.matrix=comparison, data=quant_mloG)

res_mloG <- comp_mloG$ComparisonResult
res_mloG$threshold_1 = as.factor(abs(res_mloG$log2FC) > 1 & res_mloG$pvalue < 0.01)
res_mloG$threshold_2 = as.factor(abs(res_mloG$log2FC) > 1 & res_mloG$pvalue < 0.05)
res_mloG$threshold_3 = as.factor(abs(res_mloG$log2FC) > 0.8  & res_mloG$pvalue < 0.05)
res_mloG$UPS <- ifelse(grepl("_UPS$",res_mloG$Protein), "UPS", "BKG")

spikes <- read.delim("spikes.txt")
res_mloG$Protein2 <- gsub("\\|.*","", res_mloG$Protein)
res_mloG <- merge(res_mloG, spikes, by.x="Protein2", by.y="Spike", all=TRUE)
res_mloG$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mloG$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 0
res_mloG$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mloG$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 1

res_mloG$AbsErrorRatio <- (res_mloG$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1-(2^res_mloG$log2FC))/res_mloG$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1*100
# Threshold 1
kable(table(res_mloG$threshold_1, res_mloG$UPS))

Volcano plot

with(res_mloG, plot(log2FC, -log10(pvalue), pch=20, main="Volcano plot"))
with(subset(res_mloG, pvalue < .05 ), points(log2FC, -log10(pvalue), pch=20, col="red"))
with(subset(res_mloG, abs(log2FC)>1), points(log2FC, -log10(pvalue), pch=20, col="orange"))
with(subset(res_mloG, pvalue<.05 & abs(log2FC)>1), points(log2FC, cex=2, -log10(pvalue), pch=20, col="green"))
with(subset(res_mloG, pvalue<.05 & abs(log2FC)>1), textxy(log2FC, -log10(pvalue), labs=UPS, cex=.8))
abline(h = -log10(0.05), v = c(-1,1), col = "blue", lty =2, lwd = 1.5)

Statistical test (MSstats) for differential protein abundance. Loess but with adjust.pvalue.

#detach("package:Normalyzer", unload=TRUE)

# Loess normalization
pept_loGadj <- read.delim("normalization_peptides/Loess-G-normalized.txt")

# remove peptides non-unique for groups or proteins, select Sequence, Proteins and Intensities columns, and melt table
mloGadj <- melt(subset(pept_loGadj, Unique..Groups. == "yes" & Unique..Proteins. == "yes", select=c(1,2,6:ncol(pept_loGadj))), id.vars=1:2)
mloGadj$value <- 2^mloGadj$value

#pep2prot <- aggregate(mloGadj[,4], by=list(mloGadj$Protein, mloGadj$variable), function(x) sum(x, na.rm=TRUE))
#prots <- cast(pep2prot, Group.1 ~ Group.2, sum)
#colnames(pep.prot.melt) <- c("Leading.razor.protein", "SampleName", "Condition", "sumIntensity")

# add columns for MSstats
mloGadj$PrecursorCharge <- 2
mloGadj$FragmentIon <- NA
mloGadj$ProductCharge <- NA
mloGadj$IsotopeLabelType <- "L"
mloGadj <- merge(mloGadj, sampleInfo, by="variable",all=TRUE)

# Compare 
mloGadj_10col <- mloGadj[,c(3,2,5:9,1,10,4)]
colnames(mloGadj_10col) <- c("ProteinName", "PeptideSequence", "PrecursorCharge","FragmentIon", "ProductCharge","IsotopeLabelType", "Condition","BioReplicate", "Run", "Intensity")


quant_mloGadj <- dataProcess(mloGadj_10col, normalization=FALSE)

Statistical test (MSstats) for differential protein abundance. RAW data .

#detach("package:Normalyzer", unload=TRUE)

# Loess normalization
pept_raw <- read.delim("normalization_peptides/Log2-normalized.txt")

# remove peptides non-unique for groups or proteins, select Sequence, Proteins and Intensities columns, and melt table
mraw <- melt(subset(pept_raw, Unique..Groups. == "yes" & Unique..Proteins. == "yes", select=c(1,2,6:ncol(pept_raw))), id.vars=1:2)

mraw$value <- 2^mraw$value  
#pep2prot <- aggregate(mloG[,4], by=list(mloG$Protein, mloG$variable), function(x) sum(x, na.rm=TRUE))
#prots <- cast(pep2prot, Group.1 ~ Group.2, sum)
#colnames(pep.prot.melt) <- c("Leading.razor.protein", "SampleName", "Condition", "sumIntensity")

# add columns for MSstats
mraw$PrecursorCharge <- 2
mraw$FragmentIon <- NA
mraw$ProductCharge <- NA
mraw$IsotopeLabelType <- "L"
mraw <- merge(mraw, sampleInfo, by="variable",all=TRUE)

# Compare 
mraw_10col <- mraw[,c(3,2,5:9,1,10,4)]
colnames(mraw_10col) <- c("ProteinName", "PeptideSequence", "PrecursorCharge","FragmentIon", "ProductCharge","IsotopeLabelType", "Condition","BioReplicate", "Run", "Intensity")


quant_mraw <- dataProcess(mraw_10col, normalization=FALSE)
##                        
##   Summary of Features :
##                          count
## # of Protein              2046
## # of Peptides/Protein     1-85
## # of Transitions/Peptide   1-1
##                       
##   Summary of Samples :
##                            EcoUPS1 EcoUPS2
## # of MS runs                     4       4
## # of Biological Replicates       4       4
## # of Technical Replicates        1       1
levels(quant_mraw$ProcessedData$GROUP_ORIGINAL)
## [1] "EcoUPS1" "EcoUPS2"
comparison<-matrix(c(-1,1),nrow=1)
row.names(comparison) <- "UPS2 vs UPS1"



#scopeOfTechReplication="expanded", scopeOfBioReplication="restricted", 
comp_mraw <- groupComparison(contrast.matrix=comparison, data=quant_mloG)

res_mraw <- comp_mraw$ComparisonResult
res_mraw$threshold_1 = as.factor(abs(res_mraw$log2FC) > 1 & res_mraw$pvalue < 0.01)
res_mraw$threshold_2 = as.factor(abs(res_mraw$log2FC) > 1 & res_mraw$pvalue < 0.05)
res_mraw$threshold_3 = as.factor(abs(res_mraw$log2FC) > 0.8  & res_mraw$pvalue < 0.05)
res_mraw$UPS <- ifelse(grepl("_UPS$",res_mraw$Protein), "UPS", "BKG")

spikes <- read.delim("spikes.txt")
res_mraw$Protein2 <- gsub("\\|.*","", res_mraw$Protein)
res_mraw <- merge(res_mraw, spikes, by.x="Protein2", by.y="Spike", all=TRUE)
res_mraw$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mraw$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 0
res_mraw$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mraw$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 1

res_mraw$AbsErrorRatio <- (res_mraw$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1-(2^res_mraw$Log2FC))/res_mraw$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1*100
# Threshold 1
kable(table(res_mraw$threshold_1, res_mraw$UPS))

kable(table(res_mraw$threshold_2, res_mraw$UPS))

#scopeOfTechReplication="expanded", scopeOfBioReplication="restricted",

res_mrawADJ$threshold_1 = as.factor(abs(res_mrawADJ$log2FC) > 1 & res_mrawADJ$adj.pvalue < 0.01)
res_mrawADJ$threshold_2 = as.factor(abs(res_mrawADJ$log2FC) > 1 & res_mrawADJ$adj.pvalue < 0.05)
res_mrawADJ$threshold_3 = as.factor(abs(res_mrawADJ$log2FC) > 0.8  & res_mrawADJ$adj.pvalue < 0.05)
res_mrawADJ$UPS <- ifelse(grepl("_UPS$",res_mrawADJ$Protein), "UPS", "BKG")

spikes <- read.delim("spikes.txt")
res_mrawADJ$Protein2 <- gsub("\\|.*","", res_mrawADJ$Protein)
res_mrawADJ <- merge(res_mrawADJ, spikes, by.x="Protein2", by.y="Spike", all=TRUE)
res_mrawADJ$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mrawADJ$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 0
res_mrawADJ$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mrawADJ$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 1

res_mrawADJ$AbsErrorRatio <- (res_mrawADJ$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1-(2^res_mrawADJ$Log2FC))/res_mrawADJ$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1*100

Statistical test (MSstats) for differential protein abundance. RLR-G Normalized

#detach("package:Normalyzer", unload=TRUE)

# Loess normalization
pept_RLR <- read.delim("normalization_peptides/RLR-G-normalized.txt")

# remove peptides non-unique for groups or proteins, select Sequence, Proteins and Intensities columns, and melt table
mRLR <- melt(subset(pept_RLR, Unique..Groups. == "yes" & Unique..Proteins. == "yes", select=c(1,2,6:ncol(pept_RLR))), id.vars=1:2)
mRLR$value <- 2^mRLR$value

#pep2prot <- aggregate(mRLR[,4], by=list(mRLR$Protein, mRLR$variable), function(x) sum(x, na.rm=TRUE))
#prots <- cast(pep2prot, Group.1 ~ Group.2, sum)
#colnames(pep.prot.melt) <- c("Leading.razor.protein", "SampleName", "Condition", "sumIntensity")

# add columns for MSstats
mRLR$PrecursorCharge <- 2
mRLR$FragmentIon <- NA
mRLR$ProductCharge <- NA
mRLR$IsotopeLabelType <- "L"
mRLR <- merge(mRLR, sampleInfo, by="variable",all=TRUE)

# Compare 
mRLR_10col <- mRLR[,c(3,2,5:9,1,10,4)]
colnames(mRLR_10col) <- c("ProteinName", "PeptideSequence", "PrecursorCharge","FragmentIon", "ProductCharge","IsotopeLabelType", "Condition","BioReplicate", "Run", "Intensity")


quant_mRLR <- dataProcess(mRLR_10col, normalization=FALSE)

## [1] "EcoUPS1" "EcoUPS2"
comparison<-matrix(c(-1,1),nrow=1)
row.names(comparison) <- "UPS2 vs UPS1"



#scopeOfTechReplication="expanded", scopeOfBioReplication="restricted", 
comp_mRLR <- groupComparison(contrast.matrix=comparison, data=quant_mRLR)

res_mRLR <- comp_mRLR$ComparisonResult
res_mRLR$threshold_1 = as.factor(abs(res_mRLR$log2FC) > 1 & res_mRLR$adj.pvalue < 0.01)
res_mRLR$threshold_2 = as.factor(abs(res_mRLR$log2FC) > 1 & res_mRLR$adj.pvalue < 0.05)
res_mRLR$threshold_3 = as.factor(abs(res_mRLR$log2FC) > 0.8  & res_mRLR$adj.pvalue < 0.05)
res_mRLR$UPS <- ifelse(grepl("_UPS$",res_mRLR$Protein), "UPS", "BKG")

spikes <- read.delim("spikes.txt")
res_mRLR$Protein2 <- gsub("\\|.*","", res_mRLR$Protein)
res_mRLR <- merge(res_mRLR, spikes, by.x="Protein2", by.y="Spike", all=TRUE)
res_mRLR$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mRLR$Log2FC.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 0
res_mRLR$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1[is.na(res_mRLR$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1)] <- 1

res_mRLR$AbsErrorRatio <- (res_mRLR$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1-(2^res_mRLR$log2FC))/res_mRLR$Ratio.UPS2vsUPS1*100

Plots

There are not a lot of information in the plots generated along the analysis, but althought the analysis of the results will be done in the next point, we should say something at this point.

As we could saw, the different plots didn’t give us so much information, but it is interesting to comment about the volcano plots. We can see differences between the plots of the analysis done using method that use p.value and the ones which use adjusted pvalue. The second ones have less peptides with significant adj.pvalues than the first ones, and this is obvious due to the adjust of the pvalue, this proccess normally decrease the value of the original pvalue. This is somehitng important to take in acount because it can have importance in which normalization method we have to use to generate the best results.

First threshold We can see how raw data has less false positives using adj.pvalue. Loess normalization method also has less false positives using adj.pvalue. With VSN and RLR method we see no false positives but maybe too many false negatives. We can see that adj.pvalue is more restrictive than pvalue.

Second threshold Less restrictive threshold, we can see how the false positives increase in the raw data. The raw data with adj.pval has more true positives, but does not increase the false positives. Exactly the same happens to Loess, and true positives increase in VSN and RLR methods.

Third threshold All the cases with adj.pvalue do not change, but raw and Loess cases increase the number of true positives.

Final conclusion As we could see, the use of adjusted pvalue increase the restriction of the data, giving us less false positives but also less true positives. Then,in this study the best normalization method is Loess using pvalue not adjusted, but this is a specific case maybe caused by a too well defined data (UPS proteins are sold by SIGMA). Normally, we will need to use the adjust pvalue to have the more realistic results, so at least a check of the adj.pval would be necessary.
